a compelling study of welfare officers and how they navigate the increasingly tangled political and emotional terrain of their jobs. Celeste Watkins-Hayes here reveals how welfare reform engendered a shift in focus for caseworkers from simply providing monetary aid to the much more complex process of helping recipients find work. Now both more intimately involved in their clients’ lives and wielding greater power over their well-being, welfare officers’ racial, class, and professional identities have become increasingly important factors in their work. Based on the author’s extensive fieldwork in two very different communities in the northeast, The New Welfare Bureaucrats is a boon to anyone looking to understand the impact of the institutional and policy changes wrought by welfare reform as well as the subtle social dynamics that shape the way welfare is meted out at the individual level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPublic welfare administrationxUnited States. 0aPublic welfare administrationzUnited States. 0aSocial case workxUnited States. 0aSocial case workzUnited States. 0aSocial service and race relationsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aSocial service and race relationszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  arace, class, poverty, welfare, social programs, policy, government, reform, bureaucracy, caseworkers, employment, fieldwork, nonfiction, inequality, racism, bias, discrimination, staunton, identity, community, diversity, fishertown, professionalization, unconscious, sociology, black, african american, unemployment, jobless, joblessness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.de